This paper deals with privacy-preserving publication of microdata, which is a common problem in the field of database systems (cs.DB). The paper specifically focuses on the l-diversity principle, which is a privacy principle commonly used in the literature on privacy-preserving publication. Therefore, the paper is likely to be classified under cs.DB. However, the paper also deals with the theoretical study of l-diversity and the development of approximation algorithms, which are topics that are relevant to other sub-categories such as cs.CR (cryptography and security), cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.IT (information theory), and cs.LG (machine learning).
